\section{Experimental Procedure}
\subsection{Materials and Preparation}
As shown in table \ref{tab:matprop} the solubility of long-chain alcohols strongly depends on their length, while other properties, like density and diffusion coefficient are relatively insensitive to this. By increasing the number of carbon atoms in the chain from 5 (pentanol) to 8 (octanol), one decreases the solubility (and thereby the buoyant force of the water-alcohol mixture) by two orders of magnitude. This makes these alcohols very suitable to study the possible transition between diffusion and convection.
Alcohols with purities of $\geq98\%$ (Sigma-Aldrich) were used. The density of the alcohol-water mixture (table \ref{tab:matprop}) was calculated for a mixture at $100\%$ saturation, using the molal volume $\phi_V^0$ at infinite dilution \citep{Hoiland1976, Romero2007}. The molal volume $\phi_V$ gives the volume occupied by one mole of solute in the solvent. The assumption is made that $\phi_V$ is independent of the solute concentration, which introduces a negligible error in $\Delta\rho$ of $<1\%$ when compared to the direct density measurements given by \citet{Romero2007}. 

